bio:

### Bernerd Schaefer

# OBJECTIVE
To live in an amazing place, working with an awesome team to solve tough problems for real people.

# EXPERIENCE

### Hashrocket _April 2010-present_

*  Worked on-site with a client in Abu Dhabi, instilling best practices into their team and developing a working internal process so they could deliver their product. I also helped facilitate communication between the teams spread between Abu Dhabi, Florida, and Chicago.
*  Worked on a large-scale medical records application using Rails. We used MongoDB and Mongoid to great effect to ensure the application remained speedy while allowing users to view large amounts of data regarding each patient. I also helped break the large application into separate, manageable, components which communicated together as a service to maintain a rapid development process.

*  Built an automated email distribution system for TimesDigest, a New York Times company, which has delivered to date over 2.5 million emails to hotels, cruise ships, individuals, and military men and women around the world. The 5 thousand emails which go out each night are tracked for reception and bounces to calculate delivery rates and other important statistics.

name: Nick Plante
bio: Nick Plante is cofounder of Mogoterra, a software startup creating tools to make developers' lives easier. He's also the author of Practical Rails Plugins (Apress 2008) and organizer of the annual Rails Rumble innovation competition, in addition to being a prolific open source contributor. Nick has spoken at a number of industry events (Railsconf, Ruby East, Voices That Matter, SD2China) and writes for Dr. Dobbs Journal. His personal blog is at http://blog.zerosum.org

Elliott Cable
=============
(librarian, architect, sourcerer extraordinaire, DX fiend)

Objective
---------
Elliott is interested in providing the connective glue necessary to every
team. His wide areas of interest dictate that he be able to “speak the
language” in many varied technical fields. He'll be useful anywhere there are
new things to be created!

Skills overview
---------------
I’m familiar with quite… a lot… of tools, programming languages, systems, and
frameworks. To be honest, I’m a little obsessive about learning. I’ve done my
best to keep this section short and relevant. That is, however, a lofty goal,
so keep an open mind…

### Programming
- Mastery of abstractive programming techniques
  - I’ve written over 100 distinct libraries in more languages than I can count.
    I like abstracting. A lot.
- Familiarity with behaviour-driven development
- Excellency at Ruby
  - No, seriously, I started writing this, with the intention of using the
    keywords “competency,” “familiarity,” and “mastery” to describe my various
    skillsets. Unfortunately, none of those even begins to approximate my
    comprehensive knowledge of Ruby.
- Competency with Ruby on Rails, Sinatra, Camping
- Mastery of JavaScript
- Mastery of Node.js
  - I’ve been in on the Node party since the very beginning. The moment I saw
    it, I knew it was the future of web development. I still fully believe
    that.
- Mastery of git, granular commit strategies, and branching development
  - I’ve only been using git for two years or so, but I absolutely love it.
    I have something like eighty projects on GitHub, and probably twice that
    in local repositories that’ve never been publicized. I simply enjoy
    working with it.
- Competency with traditional relational databases
- Familiarity with more exotic backend technologies (such as Redis)
  - Redis is another technology that quickly caught my eye. I expect to find
    many wonderful uses for this in many, many projects.
- Mastery of Objective-C
- Familiarity with Cocoa, Xcode, and the rest of the OS X development
  environment
- Mastery of Mac OS X and OS X systems
  - I’ve been using OS X on Apple computers for half a decade, and I’ve always
    had a hacker’s spirit. There’s not a lot I don’t know about them, these
    days.
- Familiarity with ANSI C
- Mastery of Linux systems (primarily Arch Linux) and UNIX philosophies
  - While I’m an OS X devotee, a properly tuned and maintained Linux system
    can easily be just as beautiful. I love to create such systems.
- Mastery of the Amazon EC2 APIs
  - Cloud computing (all silly buzz aside) really is the future; and Amazon
    was essentially there first (at least, on that sort of large scale.) I’ve
    been using them since 2007, and tend to work EC2 instances into all
    aspects of my tasks.
- Familiarity with cloud computing concepts
- Mastery of system/project administration tools (SSH, vim, htop, sed/AWK)
- Mastery of shell scripting techniques (Zsh, Bash)

### Design & front‐end development
While I may be primarily a programmer, I have a taste for clean, minimalist
design. There’s a reason I use Apple computers and software, despite my
comprehensive knowledge of more ‘true’ UNIX systems. My design skills will
bring a touch of elegance to your development project that may otherwise be
lacking.

- Mastery of HTML5 and associated technologies
- Mastery of XHTML(5) and SVG
  - Yes, I realize that ‘XHTML5’ is simply HTML5 serialized as XML. The
    distinction is, however, important.
- Competency with MooTools, modern DHTML techniques, and the DOM
- Mastery of CSS3 and the LESS CSS pre‐compiler
- Mastery of precise and minimal design concepts
- Obsession with typography and negative space
  - I love beautiful type. It’s extremely gratifying to see a page that one’s
    eyes can just… drink in.

### Miscellaneous
Finally, while these aren’t exactly capable of fitting into either of the
above categories, I feel they are relevant enough to merit inclusion.

- Born and raised in Anchorage, Alaska
- Trained as a classical pianist
- Attained rank of Eagle Scout in the Boy Scouts of America
- Retains a taste and talent for photography

Buzzwords
---------
I suppose I absolutely *must* include these, otherwise a large portion of
possible employers would ignore me. First off, yes, I can “do AJAX.” Even
though that’s an absolutely stupid name. Second, I’m capable of participating
in “Agile” software development practices. I also like a bowl of SCRUM with
half’n’half for breakfast.

Employment
----------
- Self‐employed, Audio Video eXpress Workshops, 2002–2006
- Entrepreneur, ecable, 2005–present
- Entrepreneur, yreality, 2003–present

Education
---------
- University of Alaska, Anchorage, Jan 2007—May 2009
- Montana State University, Aug 2006—Dec 2006
- Grace Christian High School, Sep 2001—May 2006
- Home‐schooled, youth

name: Matt Lins
bio:
I’m a developer who lives in Madison, WI. I’ve been programming in a professional environment for 5 years. However, I started programming as a hobby when I was around 10 years old.

Currently I’m a contractor for CCAP (Circuit Court Automated Programs). I develop Ruby/Rails/Sinatra applications (mostly used internally, but a couple public sites).

In the past I’ve worked on a few open source ruby projects. I’ve also developed an entire Ecommerce platform in Ruby on Rails. You can see it here:

[Eagle Optics](http://eagleoptics.com)

At work I use an Ubuntu machine and I program in VIM and use RVM to manage my rubies. I deploy using Capistrano to various server setups including Passenger, Unicorn, Mongrel (legacy apps) and Tomcat (for jRuby apps).

Outside of Ruby, I’ve started focusing on the mobile platform. I’m beginning to feel pretty comfortable with Objective-C and have one application in the App Store (yeah, another flashlight):

[Flash Torch](http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/flash-torch/id380201882?mt=8)

I’m comfortable administering servers in a *nix environment and have been doing so for about 6 years. I also have a couple of applications deployed to server instances in the Rackspace cloud.

I use a Mac at home for development and everyday needs. I also have a FreeBSD file server (with ZFS) and a couple of Ubuntu media servers.

name: Victor Hugo Borja
bio:
Victor Hugo Borja.
Software Engineer.
vborja@apache.org.
http://github.com/vic
http://twitter.com/vborja
http://www.masterbranch.com/developer/vic

A little bit about me
=====================

I'm a 28 years old Mexican guy with an strong passion for programming,
open source and innovative technologies. I have 10 years of
professional experience creating java enterprise applications mostly
focused on web portals.

For me, programming is more than just my day-work, to me, it's an art
and a craft at the same time something like it was for ancient
Japanese to build samurai swords.  I really believe programming
requires not just ability, but also creativity, beauty and discipline.

I got in love with programming since I started programming in
elementary school as a child, since then, I've found pleasure in being
able to create new things using computers, finding new challenges in
things that need to be fixed or in hunting bugs down, finding
something that requires my brain to work on new ideas, and loving the
satisfaction of getting things done.

So I focused my career on my passion for programming. I believe part
of being happy in life has do to with working on things you really
love, and for me, that is learning and programming.  My first job was
at my 16's as a java intern, I could have payed for doing that job,
hehe, all days when I left the building I was just amazed by the fact
of having found something new was possible and there was no day I
didn't learn something. Since then that has been the kind of job I've
always wanted. At 17 I entered university to do a major as software
engineer but never left working. Due to family financial problems, I
dropped school, but have since decided to learn everything I can from
open source. I learned English that way, by reading mailing lists,
books on programming and using irc while hacking at open source
software :).  Some books have changed the way I see my professional
career: In 2006 I read some of Paul Grahams' essays and his "Hackers &
Painters" book, and Chad Fowlers' "The Passionate Programmer", those
books were very significative in my life, I got convinced that great
things happen to people that actually search for them, so I'm decided
to do just that and search for a job that really shines. I know I have
the potential, the ability and motivation to do great things not just
for me, but for my family, my co-workers, and the world.


Technical Skills
================

- Java is the one I have most experience with (10 years), Ruby (5
years), but also been doing some work with python, and playing with
lisp since I got in love with emacs, hacked on some experimental
languages like ioke, fancy and am creating my own toy language.

- JavaScript - jQuery, coffe-script, AJAX

- RDBM - Oracle, Postgres.

- html5, css3. - not a designer, but like it anyways

- JRuby, Spring, JBoss, J2EE stuff.

- Unix (Main platform is Linux, command line feels like home)

OpenSource Experience
=====================

I've contributed to several open-source projects over the years. Many
of my contributions have started by some bug I find or some missing
feature on tools/libraries we need for a project to work. Others - the
most - have to do with my love for programming languages.  Most of my
opensource projects or the ones I've joined interested me because I'm
always searching interesting problems. In recent times, i've become
pretty much interested in language design and development, vm
implementations, and have just discovered I'm a language geek. I love
learning new languages, even if they never get that popular, I've
found almost every language has teached me how to solve problems from
a different perspective and hence I believe that when I learn a
language I become a better programmer.


* Darcs - A SCM implemented in haskell

Submitted some bug-fixing patches. I was learning distributed SCM, back
then git didn't existed so I tried darcs while learning some haskell
just for fun.

http://darcs.net

* Ragel - An finite-state-machine compiler to several languages.

I implemented a ruby backend to allow ragel to compile to pure ruby.

http://www.complang.org/ragel

* Rubinius - A Ruby VM implemented in ruby.

I contributed many ruby code, my initial commit was all of
enumerable.rb, also did a bit of work on the initial shotgun VM.

http://rubini.us

* Sinatra - A micro web framework in ruby.

In my day work I've done some jquery, web2.0 work, so I got interested
in Sinatra when it was born, so I played around with it and added
splat arguments routing to it.  Recently I used sinatra to build
http://color-theme-select.heroku.com as I love emacs.

http://sinatrarb.com

* Apache Buildr - A build system for Java projects using Rake and
  Maven artifacts.

I was frustrated with apache ant ever since year 2000 when I started
working with it, then in 2008 when I found Buildr and I really liked
it, but the client didn't want me to install MRI ruby on their
development hosts, they only allowed us to upload jar files, so I added
support for JRuby to Buildr. It was a major feature for Buildr, as it
impacted in the number of users for the project. I also added war/ear
support, groovy joint compilation, rspec, etc.  After that I was
elected and joined the Apache Software Foundation as commiter and
later as part of the Project Management Commitee for the Apache Buildr
project.

http://buildr.apache.or

* VTD-XML - A fast xml parser for java that can process gaint xmls
  (gigabytes).

One of your clients needed a solution to parse some database generated
xml files of ~3G and no suitable solution was found until we tested
VTD-XML. Our application required parallel xml parsing, so I adapted
vtd to allow this, and later contributed the code, the author did
applied changes into baseline.

* Ioke - A dynamic prototype based programming language for the JVM.

I've made some improvements to this cool programming language. I'm
also implementing my own programming language
(http://github.com/vic/akin) having ioke as influence but targetting
javascript platforms.

http://ioke.org

* Fancy-Lang - An smalltalk like language.

I got interested in this project because its author (@bakkdoor) wanted
it to compile down to Rubinius VM' assembly. So I sat down and read
the source code for the Rubinius ruby compiler, and after a week of
studying it, I started working on fancy's compiler to rubinius.  I've
become part of fancy team since then, been doing core changes to the
language, implementing a documentation system for it
(http://api.fancy-lang.org) and lots of other cool and new features.
After just three weeks we had all the old C++ interpreter removed and
now we fully run on rbx.

http://fancy-lang.org

* Typhon - A Python implementation for the Rubinius VM

After my experience with fancy-lang, I decided to take a real language
and give it support on the Rubinius VM. So I started this project as I
believe Rubinius is a really awesome VM.  I want to explore on
integration between ruby and python, maybe we can make of Rubinius
what Parrot originally intended to be.

http://github.com/vic/typhon


Professional Background
=======================

* Consultant, Software Engineer / Sr Java Developer. - JWM Solutions
  Mexico. 2005-2010

Most of my work as been at creating, customizing software solutions
for our clients.  This position allowed me to have direct contact with
many of JWM's clients, from requirements analysis to actual coding and

I have been able to choose, learn and adapt various technologies for
use at JWM IT projects.  As a technical leader, my responsibility has
been to choose, learn and adapt various technologies for usage at JWM

I have worked both alone and with small teams of 5-10 developers using

Have adapted some lessons from opensource to our development
teams. Promoted innovation and collaboration.  Introduced usage GIT,
agile practices like BDD, code-review, and Scrum.

My work was as chief software engineer, as the company produced many
hardware devices for our clients, I was responsible for choosing,
leading and implementing software components to interface with our
custom made devices.

I implemented a Ruby interface to Englightement Foundation Libraries
(implemented in C) to create a visually attractive, fast, multimedia

name: Trotter Cashion
bio:
I've been using Ruby and Rails since May of 2005. I started my career at Eastmedia, a consulting shop in NYC, where we built an the first open source OpenID server for Verisign and the NY Jets website. After Eastmedia, I spent two and a half years at Motionbox, a video hosting company that was recently sold to Snapfish. While there, I wrote the API and payment processing system amongst other things. In June of 2009, I left Motionbox to work on a collateral messaging product for Algorithmics, which used Clojure, RabbitMQ, Chef, and Rails. In March of 2010, I became the first employee at Hoopla Software, a small startup that develops applications for the Salesforce.com platform.

I've also contributed to three books: The Rails Way, Service-Oriented Design with Ruby and Rails, and Rails Refactoring to Resources.

I've spoken at conferences around the world on a variety of topics:

  * StrangeLoop 2010 - Chef
  * OSCON 2010 - Chef, Cucumber
  * Philly ETE 2010 - Chef
  * RailsConf Europe 2007 - Rails Resources tutorial
  * Goruco 2007 - Testing

I'm currently looking for some freelance / consulting work. I specialize in Javascript and Ruby. If you're interested, please contact me.

Please forgive the poor formatting / sparse details in this resume, I'll try to update it with more complete information later.

name: Scott McMillin
bio:
Scott has been working  in the web industry for over 15 years, first as co-founder of Hopscotch Media (1997), a Web agency, and subsequently as co-founder of both ShopLocal (1999) and Timelines (2007). For ShopLocal he designed SalesHound.com, a consumer site aggregating local sales and specials, and the industry-leading SmartCircular which is now used by every major retailer in the country to present local, print-based promotions to consumers on the Web. For Timelines, Scott developed a number of consumer products including LifeSnapz.com, a site to help families record and share life events, Timelines.com, a site for discovering, recording, and sharing history, and Photogram, an iPhone app allowing users to easily and creatively share moments with friends and family (with over 300,000 downloads so far). He also developed Timelines SE, a cost-effective service for newspapers to aggregate and present photos, videos, and articles about events to readers using timelines and maps (a finalist in the 2010 Chicago Innovation Awards). Timelines SE customers included Boston Globe, New York Daily News, Chicago Sun-Times, Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, St. Louis Post-Dispatch, and Minnesota Star Tribune. As an independent contractor he designed and developed solutions for Windstream Communications, Kraft Foods, Buena Vista International, Dow Chemical, First Analysis, and many other smaller companies.

Scott's experience and wide-ranging skill set allows him to conceive, design, develop, and implement products from start to finish. From product development, user-centered design and usability, information architecture, visual and identity design to programming, and server administration and deployment, he's all you need to kickstart your product.

## SUMMARY
I have been programming computers since 1984. 

Starting out with BASIC then ASM, Pascal, C, PHP, Javascript, and Ruby on Rails. I have built many networks including a wireless ISP in Silver Springs Nevada that I ran for about three years. In the 90's I ran a BBS using WWIV in Modesto, CA.

I have use many different computer systems starting with the Timex SinClair 1000, Commodore 64 and Pet, Radio Shack TRS-80, IBM PC from 8088 up, and the Macintosh. I have use DOS, OS/2, BeOS, Windows, Linux, BSD, and Mac OS X.

I started my company Orange Room Software in 2005 at the same time I started writing Ruby on Rails web applications.

Since 2005 I built a live simulcast auction system for GH Remarketing, the car inventory system for DealerTrend, a credit union automotive auction system for ACUAA, and many other small RoR projects along the way.

I have also wrote a handful of WordPress plugins that include a Vehicle listing system, the SnapEngage chat integration plugin, and some testimonial and property custom post type plugins. I have also build a few WordPress themes including a HTML5 parent theme that I use for the handful of web sites I host.


## SPECIALTIES
Ruby on Rails 3 & 3.1, MongoDB, AJAX, DHTML, jQuery, and shipping code.

Projects

    * http://www.racentries.com - an online event entry service for running events.
    * A number of content management sites for orienteering clubs and other organisations. http://www.heathdevelopments.co.uk being the most recent.

====== Mel Gray ======

Location: Seattle, WA (Capitol Hill)

E-mail: melgray@gmail.com

Phone: 512-769-0636

===== Objective =====

Seeking a position in life that allows me to implement creative solutions to complex problems in hopes of benefiting mankind and possibly the world.

===== Employment History =====

==== SEOmoz (www.seomoz.org) ====
__September 2007 to September 2009_

Filled duties of both a developer and a system administrator.

Was responsible for re-architecting legacy 'tool' library.  
As the company's customer base grew it was important that the tool offering grow with it.
The legacy systems were designed to work with only so many users.  Was charged with the task of 
building new tools around a pattern that would allow for a great deal of concurrent use.

Many of the tools had to fetch up to 50 pages simultaneously for a single report. 
This compounded with a great many number of users all running reports simultaneously, made getting report data back to the user in a timely fashion tricky.  
After some development time and testing, we were able to build a system that not only met the needs of users, but was easy to maintain and add onto as a developer.


==== Metadot Corporation (Metadot.com) ====
__March 2006 to September 2007__

Acted as chief administrator and "go to guy" inside the office and out.

Provided support via Helpdesk for customer's with yearly support contracts. 
Customers are located across 5 different continents and had varying degree's of support options (like remote monitoring). 
It is not rare to be paged at 3am because a server in Nigeria was down.

Developed portions of the Helpdesk I was using to provide support to these customers.

Managed an in office network of 10 PC's consisting of various Linux and Windows varieties.

Managed a collocated network of 7 servers used to host our products and provide service for our customers.

Was assigned projects of varying degree's of difficulty to meet various end goals. 
One day (or at times even hour) I could be playing with CSS for a skin, the next I would be migrating Helpdesk data from an archaic legacy system into our Mojo Helpdesk product.

The team was very small so more often than not, I would answer the phone (politely).

Helped distribute information about another one of our products, the Das Keyboard (http://daskeyboard.com )

==== World Reservations (CondoCo.com) ====
__2000 to 2005__

- McAllen, Texas era (2000-2002)
Network/System Maintenance, installation, upgrade, and troubleshooting on a LAN that Call Center Operators used to retrieve customer information.

Personally installed the physical wire infrastructure for the company's new office space.

- San Antonio, Texas era (2002-2005)
Acted as an outside contractor / consultant

Provided legacy system support and development

==== Silver Spur Guest Ranch ====
__2004 to 2005__

Basic PC maintenance, installations, and upgrades. 

Consultation on various software. 

Instruction / Tutoring on various Computer subjects.

Hosting & Maintenance service for the Ranch's website and email.

===== IT Exposure =====

==== Technical Experience ====

  === System Services ===

    == Web ==

        * mod_perl

    == Backups ==

  === Misc ===

==== Project Experience ====

  === Development ===

    - Currently own & maintain SliceApp.com
      * SliceApp allows users to install generic software on their linux servers with the push of a button.
      * Front end accepts jobs requests, initiates a ssh session on the backend, and then relays the session to the user in real time.
      * All installs are free
      * Working on an update that allows for install / configuration options (will be SasS).

    - Developed SSO solution for MIT's Mechanical Engineering Intranet.
    
    - General development and management of Mojo Helpdesk (http://www.mojohelpdesk.com)
      * At time of departure had over 4000 "accounts" each with a range of 1-20 users
      * Developed "Email to Ticket" feature.
      * General bug catching / patching.
      
    - General development and management of Metadot Portal Server project (http://www.metadot.com ).
      * 10,000+ lines of object oriented Perl
      * Thousands of sites using the software for free, yet having the courtesy to report bugs :) 
      * 100+ long term support contract users that needed immediate solutions / development for features that often did not exist within the project.
  
    - General development and management of Metadot Wiki (http://www.metadot.net)
      * Helped give design input during initial development.
      * General debugging & system administration
      * "Launched" the beta product
  
    - General development and management of Montastic Monitoring (http://www.montastic.com)
  
    - Managed all of the above while acting as the sole support provider for our contracted support customers.
  

==== Other Activities & Projects ====

  * Jogging
  * Configuring and administrating my home network to allow for "home away from home" access
  * Constantly reading about Ruby
  * Cinema
  * Music
  
===== Personal Details =====

  * 26 year old male
  * Born and raised in Texas (now residing in Seattle, WA)
  * Very open minded
  * Very un-opinionated
  * Very geeky (no neckbeard, clean cut [have transmogrified into a long hair since relocating to PNW])
  * Love technology, love life, love to laugh.
  * Although this resume is lengthy, I am at heart a minimalist.
  
===== Declaration =====

  I hereby declare that the above written particulars are true to the best of my knowledge and belief.

name: Elliot Murphy
bio: I currently specialize in building distributed/international engineering teams working on open source projects. I don't commute. I'm learning how to fly small airplanes. I have successfully patented inventions and am skeptical of the value of patents. I am not afraid of a blank slate, or a multi-million line legacy code base - I've dealt with both of those several times before, and delivered wonderfully satisfying results in record time. I have also worked on and learned from projects that failed miserably. Finally, I know operations inside and out - your code isn't worth anything unless it can be easily and reliably run in production, with predictable results.

name: Aslak Hellesøy
bio:
I am a senior software engineer at DRW Trading in London.

I have contributed to dozens of open source projects since 2001. My latest creation is (http://cukes.info/ "Cucumber"), a popular BDD tool for Ruby, the JVM and .NET.

Previous projects I have worked on are XDoclet, which inspired Java annotations and .NET attributes. I am also one of the creators of PicoContainer, a simplistic Dependency Injection container that was very influential in the early days of DI (2003). It's still pretty good actually.
I also contributed a lot of code to the RSpec project, the first BDD tool that gained widespread use.

I have been practicing agile development (XP, Scrum, Kanban) since 2003, and I'm a frequent conference speaker about agile practices and programming in general.

While I'm not _directly_ available for hire, I'm open for consulting gis via my employer, BEKK.
